So this educational session is entitled Targeted Alpha and Beta

3
00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:12.500
Emitting Radiopharmaceuticals: Multidisciplinary Precision Radiation

4
00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:13.040
Medicine.

5
00:00:17.660 --> 00:00:18.160
And

6
00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:26.380
so I'm very proud to introduce my speakers, appreciate their

7
00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:29.480
willingness to join for this. And our first speaker today,

8
00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:31.500
Dr. Delphine Chen,

9
00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:36.220
professor in nuclear medicine and radiology at the Fred Hutch

10
00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:39.400
Cancer Center, who'll be talking to us about quantitative molecular imaging to

11
00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:42.840
enable personalized radiopharmaceutical therapy with alpha and beta emitting

12
00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:43.880
isotopes. Welcome.

13
00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:50.120
Yeah, thanks. Thank you so much. Ooh, sorry about that.

14
00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:53.360
Thank you so much for the invitation to speak, and

15
00:00:54.540 --> 00:00:58.110
we'll look forward to diving into this. So here are my disclosures.

16
00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:02.340
So we're going to talk about quantitative imaging and how that could help us lead

17
00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:04.780
to personalized approaches for alpha and beta emitters.

18
00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:06.220
So we will look at

19
00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:10.800
some of the ways that molecular imaging helps us with that, how PET quantification

20
00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:13.260
can help with patient selection, and other aspects of

21
00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:17.440
predicting response and determining prognosis, and looking at

22
00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:18.560
quantitative SPECT.

23
00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:23.180
So in terms of personalizing our treatments, as you know, we are

24
00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:26.660
looking at the distribution of a radiopharmaceutical, and we can use

25
00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:30.560
imaging to help us determine whether the expression of that target is present,

26
00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:34.740
so that when we give our radiopharmaceutical drug, we know that it's

27
00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:37.070
going to target those tumor sites.

28
00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:41.600
And using that imaging, we are essentially, in a way, phenotyping

29
00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:45.480
that patient to determine what is that expression level and whether it's worth

30
00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:46.930
treating with the radioactive drugs.

31
00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:50.920
We can also look at dose delivery including drug

32
00:01:50.940 --> 00:01:54.860
retention. So that's where the dosimetry aspect comes into play, as well

33
00:01:54.880 --> 00:01:56.700
as with the radiation delivery.

34
00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:00.640
So quantitative imaging with PET and SPECT are helpful.

35
00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:04.560
PET is inherently, as you know, a quantitative imaging modality, and SPECT is also

36
00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:08.530
now quantitative as well. So in terms of ways we can

37
00:02:08.581 --> 00:02:09.750
quantify the images,

38
00:02:10.741 --> 00:02:12.900
there are different levels of quantification.

39
00:02:12.940 --> 00:02:16.420
Probably what we're most familiar is with a relative to organ scoring

40
00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:18.540
system that's used for both

41
00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:23.440
dotatate PET and PSMA PET referencing, like liver and spleen,

42
00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:26.340
and how avid is the tumor relative to those organs.

43
00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:29.020
We can also use semi-quantitative measurements.

44
00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:32.200
I think everyone's familiar with the SUV, standard uptake value.

45
00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:34.640
You can look at the maximum or the mean per lesion.

46
00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:37.720
You can also look at the mean for the total tumor volume.

47
00:02:38.060 --> 00:02:41.920
You can actually do a functionally defined or biomarker

48
00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:45.760
defined tumor volume using PSMA uptake or

49
00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:48.280
dotatate uptake to then define what your tumor volume is.

50
00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:52.640
And finally, you can use dynamic or multi-time point imaging, which is the most

51
00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:56.160
common approach and probably best approach for looking at dosimetry, and you can

52
00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:59.020
also use that for pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic measurements.

53
00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:02.460
We won't go into that pharmacokinetic and dynamic

54
00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:06.109
measurements so much, but just to be aware that those

55
00:03:06.200 --> 00:03:10.100
are assessments that you can do with

56
00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:13.850
quantitative imaging as well if you're looking at on-target interactions and

57
00:03:13.900 --> 00:03:14.900
off-target interactions.

58
00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:19.720
So let's look at intensity scoring relative to reference organs.

59
00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:22.980
We'll review NETTER-1 and two, and then the VISION trial.

60
00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:25.420
So VISION, and I should say,

61
00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:29.840
therapy also had this reference, but they actually had more

62
00:03:29.900 --> 00:03:33.580
quantitative metrics included. So in both NETTER-1 and

63
00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:37.380
NETTER-2, we looked at somatostatin receptor imaging that was used to define who

64
00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:39.780
was eligible to be treated with lutetium dotatate.

65
00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:44.160
In NETTER-1, the modality was indium-11 penetreotide, so Octreoscan,

66
00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:48.980
and they were scored. They had to have uptake that was either

67
00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:50.400
equal to the liver or above

68
00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:54.940
on all evaluable images. And as you know, this

69
00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:58.880
recruited the low-grade, Grade 1, Grade 2, well-differentiated neuroendocrine

70
00:03:58.920 --> 00:03:59.340
tumors.

71
00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:01.590
In NETTER-2,

72
00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:05.700
the modality is now switched to PET. It was now more widely available.

73
00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:09.840
They allowed also the indium-111

74
00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:13.700
penetreotide scans, as well as tech-based planar scans for

75
00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:15.640
somatostatin receptor expression assessment.

76
00:04:16.070 --> 00:04:19.840
And now they restricted the eligibility to have a

77
00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:22.160
higher level of uptake, so they required that the

78
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.140
uptake in the evaluable lesions had to be at least above the liver.

79
00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:28.380
It couldn't be similar to the liver.

80
00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:31.990
So when you look at the outcome, so everyone's familiar with these survival curves.

81
00:04:31.990 --> 00:04:35.080
Clearly, there was a benefit in receiving lutetium dotatate.

82
00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:38.000
But what's interesting is in the post hoc analysis, when you looked at the

83
00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:41.880
somatostatin receptor expression, even if you had uptake that was similar

84
00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:43.800
to liver or between liver and spleen,

85
00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:45.720
the

86
00:04:46.700 --> 00:04:50.260
benefit that you would receive from lutetium dotatate was very similar to those who

87
00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:53.800
had higher level uptake, which was above the spleen or markedly avid.

88
00:04:55.860 --> 00:04:59.680
Similarly, in NETTER-2, then when they did their post hoc analysis

89
00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:03.180
looking at the scores between score three and four, there wasn't a large

90
00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:07.300
difference in terms of the outcomes with treatment with lutetium dotatate relative

91
00:05:07.360 --> 00:05:11.100
to the intensity. So these trials suggest that in,

92
00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:14.860
at least for lutetium-177 dotatate or

93
00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:19.300
somatostatin receptor, if you want to extrapolate beyond lutetium-177

94
00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:21.180
dotatate, but at least for that drug,

95
00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:26.100
the intensity doesn't seem to have a huge impact, at least when you look at

96
00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:29.380
it from this angle relative to the reference organ.

97
00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:33.740
Just to be aware, one of the challenges with using reference organs, though, is

98
00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:36.020
that the biodistribution can be changed.

99
00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:40.080
The normal biodistribution of the tracer on imaging can

100
00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:44.140
change relative to other drugs or other biological processes or physiologic

101
00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:47.700
processes. So one of them that has been better characterized is the

102
00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:51.580
impact of having somatostatin analogs on what a

103
00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:53.920
somatostatin receptor PET image would look like.

104
00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:58.140
So because the somatostatin analogs bind to the same sites as where dotatate,

105
00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:00.580
dotatocicium, or any of the other PET agents

106
00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:04.588
bindThere was always the concern that you would have competitive

107
00:06:04.628 --> 00:06:08.498
inhibition and inability to see the uptake in the tumors if you had

108
00:06:08.808 --> 00:06:10.348
the somatostatin analogs on board.

109
00:06:10.728 --> 00:06:14.668
But what we found, and there are at least three papers that I know of, and maybe

110
00:06:14.708 --> 00:06:18.548
a few others. But the three earliest papers showed that what happened when

111
00:06:18.608 --> 00:06:21.868
you gave the somatostatin analogs is that it decreased the amount of

112
00:06:21.888 --> 00:06:25.638
activity in the background in the liver and the spleen, and then you could

113
00:06:25.788 --> 00:06:27.548
see the uptake in the tumors better.

114
00:06:27.978 --> 00:06:31.688
And when they did quantitative measurements, the SUVs would actually even go up

115
00:06:32.688 --> 00:06:36.368
with the somatostatin analogs. And that was tested even giving the

116
00:06:36.428 --> 00:06:40.248
somatostatin analog shortly, within 11 days of doing

117
00:06:40.388 --> 00:06:44.208
the dotatate or somatostatin receptor PET, and up

118
00:06:44.308 --> 00:06:47.768
to a month prior to doing the dotatate PET.

119
00:06:47.828 --> 00:06:51.768
So that is just one thing to keep in mind in terms of when you're

120
00:06:51.848 --> 00:06:53.168
using the reference organs

121
00:06:54.088 --> 00:06:56.808
for that, and we'll see a similar thing with PSMA.

122
00:06:57.328 --> 00:07:01.248
So in the post hoc analysis, just to look at other quantitative

123
00:07:01.668 --> 00:07:04.368
ways of looking at the PET information.

124
00:07:04.668 --> 00:07:08.198
When you look at the liver tumor burden, there was a post hoc

125
00:07:08.248 --> 00:07:12.208
analysis looking at what metrics in the liver would potentially predict

126
00:07:12.288 --> 00:07:16.038
response, because the presence of liver metastases,

127
00:07:16.148 --> 00:07:19.868
that tends to be the cause of mortality in neuroendocrine

128
00:07:19.908 --> 00:07:23.888
tumor. And what you can see is that the amount of liver tumor

129
00:07:23.908 --> 00:07:27.808
burden based on the segmentation with a somatostatin

130
00:07:27.848 --> 00:07:31.208
receptor agent didn't seem to have any impact on the

131
00:07:31.888 --> 00:07:35.328
clinical benefit from lutetium dotatate treatment.

132
00:07:36.348 --> 00:07:40.268
But if you had the presence of at least one large liver lesion

133
00:07:40.288 --> 00:07:44.178
greater than three centimeters, that had a significant impact on how

134
00:07:44.268 --> 00:07:48.228
well those patients responded. So these are other ways that we can

135
00:07:48.348 --> 00:07:50.588
look at quantitative imaging to help

136
00:07:51.488 --> 00:07:54.218
predict which patients are going to respond better versus not.

137
00:07:54.968 --> 00:07:58.368
Switching now to lutetium PSMA. So our two

138
00:07:58.408 --> 00:08:02.108
largest, or the two earliest trials looking at the benefit of

139
00:08:02.158 --> 00:08:06.028
lutetium PSMA for metastatic castration-resistant prostate cancer

140
00:08:06.368 --> 00:08:09.748
are the, excuse me, the VISION trial and the THERAPY trial.

141
00:08:10.248 --> 00:08:14.128
So the VISION trial was lutetium PSMA plus standard of care

142
00:08:14.148 --> 00:08:17.588
versus standard of care in the control arm, and THERAPY was lutetium

143
00:08:17.608 --> 00:08:21.228
PSMA versus cabazitaxel in those patients

144
00:08:21.288 --> 00:08:25.088
who their next best management step was going to be treatment with

145
00:08:25.108 --> 00:08:25.908
cabazitaxel.

146
00:08:27.188 --> 00:08:30.768
In terms of the imaging that was required to allow them to

147
00:08:30.808 --> 00:08:33.208
proceed with treatment with the lutetium PSMA.

148
00:08:33.808 --> 00:08:37.588
For VISION criteria , PSMA uptake had to be above the background

149
00:08:37.648 --> 00:08:41.369
liver intensity, and they couldn't have any PSMA negative disease, was

150
00:08:41.408 --> 00:08:45.268
defined by any node that was greater than two and a half centimeters, or

151
00:08:45.648 --> 00:08:46.188
solid or bone

152
00:08:47.648 --> 00:08:50.188
soft tissue lesions that were greater than a centimeter.

153
00:08:50.538 --> 00:08:54.188
And that is, of course, to overcome the potential partial volume averaging effects

154
00:08:54.248 --> 00:08:57.468
you might have with smaller lesions on PET imaging.

155
00:08:58.208 --> 00:09:00.448
FDG PET was not used for eligibility.

156
00:09:00.548 --> 00:09:03.137
It was purely based on the PSMA PET findings.

157
00:09:03.708 --> 00:09:04.488
In THERAPY,

158
00:09:06.468 --> 00:09:10.228
like I said, they had actually these quantitative criteria.

159
00:09:10.608 --> 00:09:14.068
So not so much just relying on the reference organs, but

160
00:09:14.148 --> 00:09:17.808
you had to have at least one measurable lesion with a maximum SUV

161
00:09:17.908 --> 00:09:21.608
of over 20 on the PSMA PET, and all the other measurable

162
00:09:21.708 --> 00:09:23.988
lesions had to have a maximum SUV over 10.

163
00:09:24.368 --> 00:09:28.028
They also did FDG PET and required that there was no discordant

164
00:09:28.128 --> 00:09:30.728
FDG positive, PSMA negative disease sites.

165
00:09:31.928 --> 00:09:35.518
So when looking at the outcomes, we are again, very familiar with

166
00:09:36.368 --> 00:09:39.508
these survival curves in terms of the benefit of lutetium PSMA.

167
00:09:40.908 --> 00:09:43.108
And drilling down into whether the

168
00:09:43.968 --> 00:09:47.108
features on the PSMA PET would predict better response or not.

169
00:09:47.788 --> 00:09:51.417
This is a post hoc analysis of the VISION trial data showing that

170
00:09:51.468 --> 00:09:55.448
what they did was they split the degree of uptake on PSMA

171
00:09:55.508 --> 00:09:59.268
PET by quartiles. And so when you look at the highest quartile, both

172
00:09:59.368 --> 00:10:03.137
for radiographic progression-free survival and overall survival, the

173
00:10:03.137 --> 00:10:05.158
highest quartile had the best outcomes.

174
00:10:05.528 --> 00:10:09.228
And interestingly, there was less of a differentiator between the lower

175
00:10:09.268 --> 00:10:11.908
three quartiles, as you can see from these curves.

176
00:10:11.928 --> 00:10:15.658
What's also interesting is that this is the mean SUV of the PSMA defined

177
00:10:15.748 --> 00:10:19.408
total tumor volume, and you can see that the mean is actually around

178
00:10:19.428 --> 00:10:21.048
10, which kind of aligns

179
00:10:22.528 --> 00:10:25.408
pretty well with the cutoffs that they used in the THERAPY trial,

180
00:10:26.308 --> 00:10:28.248
even though the THERAPY trial was designed earlier.

181
00:10:28.868 --> 00:10:28.968
So

182
00:10:30.528 --> 00:10:34.088
when you look at outcomes from THERAPY, they did a post hoc analysis of the

183
00:10:34.188 --> 00:10:37.708
imaging biomarkers and the ability of those for both

184
00:10:37.768 --> 00:10:41.428
PSMA and FDG to predict response. This is based on the

185
00:10:41.468 --> 00:10:45.208
PSMA PET, so the top row are the patients with lower

186
00:10:45.368 --> 00:10:48.988
SUV means on PSMA, and then above. So

187
00:10:50.168 --> 00:10:53.488
like I said, the SUV mean was not a cutoff, but this is the cutoff they used in the

188
00:10:53.528 --> 00:10:56.508
post hoc analysis, and you can see that it reasonably

189
00:10:56.548 --> 00:11:00.438
differentiates those who had larger responses in

190
00:11:00.468 --> 00:11:02.358
patients who were treated with lutetium PSMA.

191
00:11:02.748 --> 00:11:06.008
The other interesting thing about this, though, is that you can see that there's

192
00:11:06.128 --> 00:11:08.408
still a good subset of patients in the

193
00:11:08.428 --> 00:11:12.408
cabazitaxel treatment group who also had a respond

194
00:11:12.448 --> 00:11:15.638
to their treatment regardless of the PSMA expression.

195
00:11:17.008 --> 00:11:20.088
But probably the bigger determinant of whether

196
00:11:21.728 --> 00:11:25.668
lutetium PSMA would give you a better outcome or not was based on the

197
00:11:25.728 --> 00:11:29.568
FDG data. So now when they looked at the metabolic

198
00:11:29.668 --> 00:11:33.408
tumor volume defined by FDG and looked at smaller versus larger

199
00:11:33.528 --> 00:11:37.208
tumor volumes, you can see that with a smaller FDG tumor volume,

200
00:11:37.968 --> 00:11:41.928
a significantly larger number of those patients actually had a positive response

201
00:11:41.968 --> 00:11:43.128
to lutetium PSMA.

202
00:11:44.078 --> 00:11:47.148
But this actually held over even across with cabazitaxel.

203
00:11:47.228 --> 00:11:51.028
So in general, patients with lower FDG metabolic tumor volumes will generally do

204
00:11:51.048 --> 00:11:54.880
better to treatment compared to those with higher....

205
00:11:54.890 --> 00:11:58.760
treatments. Our group, Dr. Irvani is our diagnostics director and

206
00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:02.420
has led a lot of this work in looking at our data for how you use

207
00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:04.570
imaging biomarkers to predict response.

208
00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:08.380
So this is a recent publication looking at now stratifying patients.

209
00:12:08.440 --> 00:12:11.920
So our clinical practice uses the VISION criteria for

210
00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:15.700
determining whether patients are eligible for being treated with lutetium PSMA,

211
00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:19.620
with some modifications for where they are clinically.

212
00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:23.720
So if they don't have any other good options, they're in reasonable health,

213
00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:27.720
even if the PSMA uptake is lower, we may proceed with treatment as long as there

214
00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:30.960
is actually PSMA uptake. So there may be some minor modifications.

215
00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:34.620
And you will see that in clinical practice, in the published data, that

216
00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:38.870
clinically, sometimes we use other factors besides the imaging to decide whether

217
00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:40.680
we're going to proceed with lutetium PSMA.

218
00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:44.980
But generally, we still want them to have enough

219
00:12:44.990 --> 00:12:46.940
uptake to justify proceeding with treatment.

220
00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:48.160
So,

221
00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:52.860
as I said, in our practice, all of them in this cohort were

222
00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:56.680
eligible by the VISION criteria, and then they further stratified about whether

223
00:12:56.720 --> 00:12:58.500
they would have been eligible for

224
00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:03.340
being treated with lutetium PSMA in the therapy trial using the

225
00:13:03.400 --> 00:13:07.160
therapy eligibility criteria. So here are the cases

226
00:13:07.220 --> 00:13:07.760
looking at--

227
00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:11.460
This is a classic. This would be easily eligible by

228
00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:15.860
either clinical trial or just in general for clinical assessment highly

229
00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:18.450
PSMA-avid disease, no FDG uptake.

230
00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:23.050
But then with therapy, if you had high PSMA uptake but

231
00:13:23.060 --> 00:13:26.200
concordant FDG, you could still proceed as long as the uptake was high enough on

232
00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:29.900
the PSMA. And then the therapy in eligible patients, so low

233
00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:31.670
PSMA with greater

234
00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:36.520
FDG, or just-- Sorry, low PSMA and even

235
00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:39.440
regardless of what the FDG shows, and then discordant disease.

236
00:13:40.700 --> 00:13:44.500
So in looking at the outcomes based on those stratifications, you can see that in

237
00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:48.100
general, those who met the therapy eligibility

238
00:13:48.180 --> 00:13:52.020
criteria actually did better across the board, both for survival and

239
00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:54.980
PSA-defined progression-free survival.

240
00:13:55.670 --> 00:13:59.380
And then when you further stratify this into those who were

241
00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:03.320
therapy ineligible because of low PSMA expression versus

242
00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:07.089
those that had discordant FDG positive, PSMA negative

243
00:14:07.180 --> 00:14:07.640
disease,

244
00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:12.670
you can see that those with discordant disease actually did worse

245
00:14:12.680 --> 00:14:14.900
than those that simply had low PSMA.

246
00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:19.990
And then when you further look at this in survival, looking specifically within

247
00:14:20.040 --> 00:14:22.400
the discordant disease, you can see that those

248
00:14:24.460 --> 00:14:24.940
with

249
00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:31.820
discordant

250
00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:35.800
disease had poor outcomes overall, when you look at the

251
00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:36.860
entire data set.

252
00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:41.460
There's another study that looked at the rates of PSMA and FDG discordant

253
00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:45.320
disease. I won't go into that in detail just for time, but they also did-- This

254
00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:49.200
was in German centers, and they found actually very few patients with

255
00:14:49.240 --> 00:14:53.200
discordant disease. So their conclusion was that FDG could be

256
00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:54.720
helpful still, but they didn't have

257
00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:58.700
strong data to suggest that

258
00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:02.560
FDG was helpful, and that PSMA stratification could

259
00:15:02.620 --> 00:15:04.120
be enough. But

260
00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:09.120
I think this is still evolving data in terms of how FDG PET will be used.

261
00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:09.340
But

262
00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:12.960
I think the data is there to suggest that if you do have higher

263
00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:17.840
volumes of highly FDG-avid disease, probably you're going to do more poorly.

264
00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:23.190
Okay. Moving on to dosimetry. So dosimetry, of course, is what we've

265
00:15:23.220 --> 00:15:26.710
talked about a lot. It's conceptually highly appealing, and on a

266
00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:29.840
physics and biological basis, it makes a lot of sense.

267
00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:33.920
If you can deliver and you can measure that you're going to deliver very high

268
00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:37.420
radiation doses to your tumor sites, that should be able to help you to

269
00:15:37.860 --> 00:15:41.800
tailor the dose. Especially if you know that you're going to avoid, because

270
00:15:41.860 --> 00:15:45.360
of the degree of uptake in your tumor sites, that you're going to

271
00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:49.420
minimize the uptake in your non-off-target sites and minimize the rate

272
00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:51.580
of toxicities, that is really appealing.

273
00:15:52.420 --> 00:15:56.040
And we want to be able to do that to be able to give the maximum

274
00:15:56.380 --> 00:15:58.420
clinical benefit whenever we treat these patients.

275
00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:02.630
It's been challenged by lack of standardized approaches, lots of

276
00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:06.260
variability in terms of both on the image acquisition side, how you

277
00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:09.880
calculate those radiation doses.

278
00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:13.820
And also, there's no data showing that when you do the dosimetry, it

279
00:16:14.279 --> 00:16:15.900
actually has an impact on outcomes.

280
00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:19.500
That said, we're in the early stages, I think, of getting this data.

281
00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:24.060
And so that's where I think the field is in terms of there are lots of efforts

282
00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:26.800
trying to put these kinds of trials together.

283
00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:30.820
So I'm just going to go over a few papers.

284
00:16:30.860 --> 00:16:33.800
This is not going to be an exhaustive review of every single paper out there, but I

285
00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:36.820
think I want to highlight some of the things that we have done and some of the

286
00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:40.080
directions we want to go. So first, dosimetry, as I mentioned,

287
00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:44.060
the classic way to calculate dosimetry is multiple time point

288
00:16:44.100 --> 00:16:48.080
imaging, so you can get a good assessment of the retention of your drug

289
00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:51.990
in the tumor sites over time. So for a clinical practice,

290
00:16:52.040 --> 00:16:55.060
that can be challenging to do every single person, because then they're coming back

291
00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:58.860
for multiple time points over the course of a week to decide what that

292
00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:02.400
dose is going to be and to estimate both the tumor

293
00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:06.901
radiation doses as well as your normal organ

294
00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:11.440
doses. So this study actually looked at single time point

295
00:17:12.340 --> 00:17:15.440
estimations to see if that could be helpful in terms of

296
00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:19.240
identifying those patients that are getting adequate tumor uptake

297
00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:23.181
versus not, and whether it's feasible in terms of calculating dosimetry.

298
00:17:23.260 --> 00:17:27.181
So they took single time point that was generally at about 24 hours after

299
00:17:28.120 --> 00:17:32.010
each cycle, and they used population-based curves to generate their

300
00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:35.820
dosimetry estimates. And what you can see is that interestingly, they saw that

301
00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:39.740
with each cycle over time, the amount of radiation that was delivered, the

302
00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.780
lesion absorbed doses decreased with each cycle.

303
00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:46.420
And these are just some cases of some that responded really well to the

304
00:17:46.440 --> 00:17:50.160
lutetium dotatate versus-- Sorry, I think it was a slightly

305
00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:53.540
different peptide, but the lutetium-based dotatate versus--

306
00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:56.050
Sorry, take that back. It was lutetium dotatate.

307
00:17:56.400 --> 00:17:56.600
So

308
00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:01.400
you can see that some were great responders, where they, in terms of the amount of

309
00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:05.292
uptake, so theThus leading to decreased

310
00:18:05.472 --> 00:18:07.932
absorbed doses in the lesions over time.

311
00:18:07.952 --> 00:18:11.852
But others had very stable disease, and stable levels

312
00:18:11.892 --> 00:18:13.471
of delivery of radiation dose.

313
00:18:15.382 --> 00:18:17.472
The overall survival, of course, is 68%.

314
00:18:17.572 --> 00:18:21.512
What's interesting about this study is that they actually had a decent

315
00:18:21.552 --> 00:18:25.432
subset. Over 60% of patients, I think, were also receiving a

316
00:18:25.692 --> 00:18:29.312
radiation sensitizer, so like hypoxanthine or 5-FU.

317
00:18:29.812 --> 00:18:33.752
So that might not apply to general practice, but it was interesting to see

318
00:18:33.812 --> 00:18:36.492
how they were able to calculate these

319
00:18:37.512 --> 00:18:38.252
measurements. The

320
00:18:39.172 --> 00:18:42.592
interesting thing too about this is that they did look at SUV and whether that

321
00:18:42.612 --> 00:18:46.512
could be an appropriate proxy for estimating the dosimetry.

322
00:18:46.542 --> 00:18:50.352
And it turned out the SUV, in the multivariate analysis, did not help

323
00:18:50.392 --> 00:18:53.052
in separating who responded or who didn't.

324
00:18:54.852 --> 00:18:58.772
There are two other papers I'll review really quickly looking at the

325
00:18:58.832 --> 00:19:00.872
maximum tolerated dose for renal dosing.

326
00:19:00.972 --> 00:19:01.302
So this

327
00:19:02.632 --> 00:19:06.612
one was designed to allow patients to get as many cycles up until

328
00:19:06.692 --> 00:19:10.332
their kidneys reached 23 gray. And they did full

329
00:19:10.412 --> 00:19:11.992
SPECT to calculate their dosimetry.

330
00:19:12.042 --> 00:19:15.492
And I'll just call your attention to the top, showing that those who were able to

331
00:19:15.512 --> 00:19:19.022
achieve that maximum tolerated dose actually had

332
00:19:19.172 --> 00:19:22.732
better improved progression-free survival and overall survival

333
00:19:22.772 --> 00:19:26.672
compared to those who did not. This other

334
00:19:26.792 --> 00:19:30.372
study they called the LUMINET trial, which recruited 96

335
00:19:30.432 --> 00:19:34.192
patients. Also, this one used planar imaging for the dosimetry

336
00:19:34.272 --> 00:19:34.792
estimates,

337
00:19:35.792 --> 00:19:37.842
and you can see that there is a nice

338
00:19:39.172 --> 00:19:42.692
subset of patients who actually have a good response

339
00:19:42.752 --> 00:19:46.452
to getting their number of cycles, and you can see the range of

340
00:19:46.652 --> 00:19:49.132
cycles is three to eight. So

341
00:19:50.312 --> 00:19:53.132
one of the other reasons I wanted to pull these two out is that because we use a

342
00:19:53.252 --> 00:19:56.732
standard protocol of four cycles, and at least during these follow-up periods,

343
00:19:56.812 --> 00:20:00.472
which was in the range of 30 to 40 months of follow-up for each of these

344
00:20:00.532 --> 00:20:00.902
trials,

345
00:20:01.732 --> 00:20:05.392
you can see that patients can get more than the four cycles

346
00:20:05.412 --> 00:20:08.272
and not necessarily have toxicity.

347
00:20:08.312 --> 00:20:12.201
Of course, we still need probably longer-term follow-up, but in

348
00:20:12.291 --> 00:20:15.092
one of the papers, they had a small number who developed MDS.

349
00:20:15.532 --> 00:20:18.892
But in terms of looking at the renal site, there was not minimal renal

350
00:20:18.952 --> 00:20:19.632
toxicity.

351
00:20:20.912 --> 00:20:23.492
Then moving on to lutetium PSMA dosimetry.

352
00:20:23.572 --> 00:20:26.112
There are a lot of papers looking at this.

353
00:20:26.352 --> 00:20:30.322
This is a review article showing that you can see that this is sort

354
00:20:30.352 --> 00:20:33.812
of a global look at looking at PSA response.

355
00:20:33.832 --> 00:20:36.741
And of course, those who don't have a PSA response tend to have lower

356
00:20:38.272 --> 00:20:41.272
delivered dose compared to those who have a response.

357
00:20:41.292 --> 00:20:44.912
And in a meta-analysis, they showed that across 29 studies looking at

358
00:20:44.952 --> 00:20:48.772
lutetium PSMA 617 versus INT, another

359
00:20:48.992 --> 00:20:50.652
lutetium PSMA drug, and

360
00:20:51.592 --> 00:20:53.172
hopefully close to clinical

361
00:20:54.192 --> 00:20:56.142
implementation, but we're still waiting for approval.

362
00:20:57.732 --> 00:21:01.252
You can see that there are similar dosimetry estimates between those two

363
00:21:01.332 --> 00:21:03.812
studies. So the SNMMI wanted to

364
00:21:04.372 --> 00:21:08.352
get a handle of what is the variability that we

365
00:21:08.372 --> 00:21:12.212
can expect to see in dosimetry estimates if each center is going to be

366
00:21:12.232 --> 00:21:16.212
performing personalized dosimetry on their own patients with their platforms,

367
00:21:16.282 --> 00:21:19.581
their scanners. And the motivation behind this was that

368
00:21:20.592 --> 00:21:23.752
since we don't have the data to say what that variability is, we can't put

369
00:21:23.792 --> 00:21:27.152
confidence intervals on what our

370
00:21:28.012 --> 00:21:30.572
individual dosimetry estimates are at each site.

371
00:21:31.052 --> 00:21:34.992
So they really set this up to look at tasks,

372
00:21:35.292 --> 00:21:38.852
everything from starting with the image acquisition, like acquisition

373
00:21:38.932 --> 00:21:42.852
protocols, to the final estimate of dosimetry, including software,

374
00:21:43.192 --> 00:21:47.032
how you segment, how you collect the data, and how you represent it, how you

375
00:21:47.092 --> 00:21:50.372
use the phantom data to ground your patient data.

376
00:21:53.052 --> 00:21:56.992
Obviously, this article summarizes the entire dosimetry

377
00:21:57.032 --> 00:22:00.542
challenge, and these were the initial results showing that we did get fairly

378
00:22:00.732 --> 00:22:03.952
similar estimates across when allowing

379
00:22:04.852 --> 00:22:08.801
teams to just do the tasks the way they were going to do it with

380
00:22:08.812 --> 00:22:09.682
certain parameters. They

381
00:22:10.552 --> 00:22:14.012
required segmentation. They looked at segmentation variability.

382
00:22:14.022 --> 00:22:17.912
They looked at the estimate, like which software platform they used to

383
00:22:17.972 --> 00:22:21.112
calculate dosimetry, whether it was voxel-based versus region-based.

384
00:22:21.592 --> 00:22:24.372
And so what they found was that overall, there were actually fairly similar

385
00:22:25.292 --> 00:22:26.822
estimates, which is really encouraging.

386
00:22:26.972 --> 00:22:27.512
So

387
00:22:28.772 --> 00:22:30.892
we're really excited to see this move forward because

388
00:22:31.032 --> 00:22:35.022
knowing how variable it will be will really help

389
00:22:35.212 --> 00:22:39.052
give us confidence in terms of the consistency of

390
00:22:39.092 --> 00:22:42.902
clinical implementation across centers, and certainly will also help

391
00:22:42.932 --> 00:22:43.252
with

392
00:22:44.152 --> 00:22:46.042
how we implement this in clinical trials.

393
00:22:47.112 --> 00:22:50.232
Finally, I'll talk briefly about alpha emitter therapies.

394
00:22:50.292 --> 00:22:52.982
So a lot of the conversation around alpha emitters,

395
00:22:53.592 --> 00:22:57.292
obviously, we're really excited about that because you can get even more

396
00:22:57.352 --> 00:23:01.112
targeted delivery of radiation to the tumor cells with hopefully

397
00:23:01.252 --> 00:23:05.112
fewer side effects if those alpha emitters stay where they're supposed to

398
00:23:05.152 --> 00:23:07.092
go and are not hitting off-target tissues.

399
00:23:07.692 --> 00:23:11.432
One of the questions about actinium-225 is that it has four daughter

400
00:23:11.532 --> 00:23:13.732
alpha emitters that come off as it decays.

401
00:23:13.812 --> 00:23:17.452
So francium-221 and bismuth-213 are emissions that

402
00:23:17.612 --> 00:23:21.332
actually can be imaged on SPECT. And so as part of the ACTION-1 trial, they

403
00:23:21.392 --> 00:23:25.292
imaged these emissions and actually showed that those emissions stay

404
00:23:25.312 --> 00:23:27.352
predominantly where the tumor is.

405
00:23:27.382 --> 00:23:31.312
So they don't actually distribute in a way that leads to a

406
00:23:31.372 --> 00:23:32.372
higher level of

407
00:23:33.592 --> 00:23:36.812
distribution to normal organs compared to tumor sites.

408
00:23:37.362 --> 00:23:41.072
And these are early data, so they showed that here are the hematologic and

409
00:23:41.132 --> 00:23:44.852
renal parameters. There are some minor toxicities, but nothing that is clinically

410
00:23:44.892 --> 00:23:46.892
significant. And you can see at least

411
00:23:48.172 --> 00:23:51.942
based on investigator determination of response, there is

412
00:23:52.092 --> 00:23:55.812
a subset of patients who are responding, and these are patients who've already

413
00:23:55.932 --> 00:23:57.792
progressed on lutetium dotatate.

414
00:23:57.872 --> 00:24:01.472
So this shows that there is the potential benefit of actinium

415
00:24:01.492 --> 00:24:05.152
dotatate to treat patients who have progressed on a beta

416
00:24:05.212 --> 00:24:08.832
emitter therapy.Okay, finally, PET for

417
00:24:08.892 --> 00:24:12.172
upfront dosimetry, I think is also a big

418
00:24:12.952 --> 00:24:16.892
topic that is slowly being evaluated in various early-phase

419
00:24:16.952 --> 00:24:18.492
clinical trials. And

420
00:24:19.952 --> 00:24:23.792
generally, a lot of the dosimetry has been based on the lutetium drug, and

421
00:24:23.812 --> 00:24:27.792
when that's the case, you really can't do upfront dosimetry for that first

422
00:24:27.812 --> 00:24:31.172
cycle if you're going to focus on just using the lutetium drug because you'd have

423
00:24:31.192 --> 00:24:33.912
to give it and then measure the dosimetry afterwards.

424
00:24:34.832 --> 00:24:38.632
There are thoughts out there potentially to use microdoses of lutetium,

425
00:24:38.732 --> 00:24:42.232
and so there's no publicly available data for that yet,

426
00:24:43.032 --> 00:24:45.572
but I think those are just being considered in clinical trials.

427
00:24:46.032 --> 00:24:49.612
But PET can certainly lend itself to helping us estimate the

428
00:24:49.632 --> 00:24:53.572
dosimetry. So as copper-64 and zirconium-89 have longer

429
00:24:53.692 --> 00:24:57.452
half-lives than gallium-68 is just too short of a half-life for us to be

430
00:24:57.492 --> 00:25:00.642
able to image far out enough to understand what

431
00:25:00.692 --> 00:25:04.552
the drug retention is. So the use of these

432
00:25:05.812 --> 00:25:07.392
isotopes has been

433
00:25:09.072 --> 00:25:12.271
incorporated into clinical trials and has been published, and so there is the

434
00:25:12.292 --> 00:25:12.692
potential

435
00:25:14.192 --> 00:25:18.072
to use PET for doing that upfront dosimetry to really

436
00:25:18.132 --> 00:25:19.912
optimize what you give that first cycle.

437
00:25:19.952 --> 00:25:23.232
And I think that's a really attractive idea because usually that first dose is

438
00:25:23.292 --> 00:25:27.092
really important, and we want to get the most effective dosing

439
00:25:27.172 --> 00:25:30.832
upfront. So data is

440
00:25:30.912 --> 00:25:34.522
still being generated, and so I'm really excited to look and see how this

441
00:25:34.572 --> 00:25:38.532
evolves. So in conclusion, we have a lot of different ways to quantify

442
00:25:38.572 --> 00:25:42.412
molecular imaging data. I've shown some of the semi-quantitative and more

443
00:25:42.432 --> 00:25:43.312
advanced quantitative

444
00:25:44.112 --> 00:25:47.572
ways we can do this. Obviously, the simpler ones are going to be easier

445
00:25:48.192 --> 00:25:51.452
to implement clinically and also have a lower burden on our patients.

446
00:25:51.512 --> 00:25:55.312
If they don't have to come back for multiple scans over a week,

447
00:25:55.372 --> 00:25:58.782
that's really helpful on their personal life and

448
00:25:58.812 --> 00:26:02.702
minimizing some toxicity in terms of

449
00:26:02.732 --> 00:26:06.242
taking up their extra time. At the same time, we're

450
00:26:06.332 --> 00:26:09.732
still in the midst of trying to figure out if those semi-quantitative or

451
00:26:10.052 --> 00:26:13.232
abbreviated measures are going to be accurate enough to give us the

452
00:26:14.172 --> 00:26:17.112
level of data we need to really tailor the dose.

453
00:26:17.172 --> 00:26:19.132
So I think this field is rapidly evolving.

454
00:26:19.552 --> 00:26:23.412
We're really excited to have multiple groups working on this.

455
00:26:24.212 --> 00:26:26.212
And so stay tuned, more to come.

456
00:26:27.192 --> 00:26:29.272
Great. Thank you very much.

457
00:26:33.912 --> 00:26:35.972
Thank you, Professor Chen. But you-

458
00:26:36.492 --> 00:26:37.372
Do you want me to stay up here?

459
00:26:37.392 --> 00:26:38.452
Either way. Come over here.

460
00:26:38.712 --> 00:26:40.532
I'll borrow-- Yeah, since I can't see everyone.

461
00:26:40.572 --> 00:26:41.532
Open this for questions.

462
00:26:41.572 --> 00:26:42.352
I'm not tall enough.

463
00:26:43.712 --> 00:26:43.852
Hi.

464
00:26:44.692 --> 00:26:47.692
Just testing. Okay. Dr. Chen, great presentation.

465
00:26:48.192 --> 00:26:51.952
Question for you about some of the co-administered molecules

466
00:26:52.012 --> 00:26:55.552
that people are using to alter the background organ uptake.

467
00:26:55.592 --> 00:26:59.512
So you talked about octreotide, but we know some people are using lysine arginine

468
00:26:59.532 --> 00:27:03.432
or Lysocare. Maybe some people might use something like Jellofusin

469
00:27:03.912 --> 00:27:06.852
to change the uptake. Are you guys looking at

470
00:27:08.672 --> 00:27:11.822
the impact of those on some of the measurements that you have?

471
00:27:13.412 --> 00:27:17.342
Yeah, that's a great question. I'm not aware of other data, so I'll defer to

472
00:27:17.372 --> 00:27:19.852
my colleagues up here if they're aware of any other data

473
00:27:20.012 --> 00:27:23.622
besides the octreotide and even any of the

474
00:27:23.672 --> 00:27:26.932
chemotherapies that we give, because there are lots of combination trials that are

475
00:27:26.952 --> 00:27:29.292
being proposed for lutetium.

476
00:27:30.472 --> 00:27:33.972
So I don't think we have a lot of data to say how that's going to affect the

477
00:27:34.072 --> 00:27:37.532
biodistribution yet. But it's a really great question, and I think it's something

478
00:27:37.572 --> 00:27:40.752
we need to pay attention to. Thanks. Yeah.

479
00:27:41.152 --> 00:27:43.462
I'll offer just one brief addition about that is,

480
00:27:44.312 --> 00:27:48.132
even though there's different ways to augment or change what the uptake is going to

481
00:27:48.152 --> 00:27:51.472
be, the FDA label does have some very specific recommendations for approved agents.

