five. Patients in the VISION trial were actually

974
00:55:57.088 --> 00:55:59.968
treated with four cycles with an additional optional two.

975
00:56:00.788 --> 00:56:04.408
The community has taken this as a de facto, we should treat them with up to six

976
00:56:04.448 --> 00:56:08.007
cycles. But in the VISION trial, it was a median of five.

977
00:56:08.588 --> 00:56:12.428
In our own institutional database, that is also five.

978
00:56:12.888 --> 00:56:16.688
So we're just about on average. The primary

979
00:56:16.948 --> 00:56:19.808
dose-limiting toxicities are thrombocytopenia

980
00:56:20.768 --> 00:56:21.668
and then anemia.

981
00:56:22.688 --> 00:56:23.728
Rarely xerostomia.

982
00:56:24.688 --> 00:56:28.188
Most patients are terminating treatment early due to disease progression, which is

983
00:56:28.288 --> 00:56:31.748
about that one quarter to one third that are not responding.

984
00:56:32.408 --> 00:56:35.928
Clinicians will get a best understanding of if a disease will

985
00:56:35.948 --> 00:56:38.848
respond to treatment after about two cycles.

986
00:56:38.888 --> 00:56:41.538
So we have this mantra in our clinic, "Every man deserves two cycles

987
00:56:42.388 --> 00:56:44.068
before assessing treatment response."

988
00:56:45.228 --> 00:56:45.488
Thank you.

989
00:56:47.087 --> 00:56:48.688
There's some great questions online.

990
00:56:50.948 --> 00:56:54.888
So, for stromal targets like FAP versus cellular targets like PSMA,

991
00:56:55.708 --> 00:56:59.308
what are your thoughts on whether radioligand therapy can be effective,

992
00:56:59.948 --> 00:57:02.008
alpha or beta, given their range?

993
00:57:03.488 --> 00:57:07.418
Great. So the question was revolving on, I guess, my general thoughts

994
00:57:07.488 --> 00:57:09.308
on if FAP is going to be effective.

995
00:57:11.368 --> 00:57:13.428
I'm hopeful we have FAP trials that are open.

996
00:57:13.528 --> 00:57:14.388
We had a FAP trial

997
00:57:16.748 --> 00:57:20.708
previously that unfortunately closed early, largely due to

998
00:57:21.028 --> 00:57:24.828
poor tumor absorbed doses of less than two to four

999
00:57:24.888 --> 00:57:27.978
gray per lesion. So those really not tumoricidal at all.

1000
00:57:28.728 --> 00:57:31.888
So early FAP compounds really suffered

1001
00:57:31.988 --> 00:57:35.798
from low tumor retention and then

1002
00:57:35.848 --> 00:57:37.128
poor subsequent

1003
00:57:38.488 --> 00:57:39.468
administered dose.

1004
00:57:40.608 --> 00:57:44.308
Newer compounds, and as a disclosure, we have the Eli Lilly

1005
00:57:44.448 --> 00:57:47.428
FIREBOLT trial, that's open and we've already accrued to it.

1006
00:57:49.068 --> 00:57:52.728
The ligand has retention going up to seven days, so we think that the

1007
00:57:53.928 --> 00:57:57.788
dosimetry will be improved and perhaps the cell killing will be better.

1008
00:57:59.788 --> 00:58:03.228
FAP expression in prostate cancer is quite variable, so

1009
00:58:04.688 --> 00:58:06.348
we're mostly looking at

1010
00:58:07.968 --> 00:58:11.958
FAP targets not in prostate cancer, for example, GI cancers,

1011
00:58:13.868 --> 00:58:17.828
melanomas, as well as certain types of breast

1012
00:58:17.888 --> 00:58:18.278
cancer.

1013
00:58:19.628 --> 00:58:23.428
There's probably going to be differential killing, of course,

1014
00:58:23.468 --> 00:58:27.408
between alpha and beta emitters in

1015
00:58:27.448 --> 00:58:31.328
FAP molecules. We just don't have enough data yet to say what's

1016
00:58:31.368 --> 00:58:34.598
going to happen. And I also want to highlight one last point is

1017
00:58:34.648 --> 00:58:38.157
that all FAP is not equal and all

1018
00:58:38.208 --> 00:58:39.998
cancer-associated fibroblasts are not equal.

1019
00:58:40.168 --> 00:58:43.588
So there's different types of cancer-associated fibroblasts along different types

1020
00:58:43.628 --> 00:58:44.068
of tissues.

1021
00:58:46.608 --> 00:58:48.088
Yeah, thank you for the excellent talk.

1022
00:58:49.908 --> 00:58:53.528
In the previous answer, you said that the treatment response is

1023
00:58:53.548 --> 00:58:55.468
assessed after the second cycle.

1024
00:58:55.828 --> 00:58:55.988
Mm-hmm.

1025
00:58:56.408 --> 00:59:00.368
Can you explain how that is done by PET imaging and the relevance of

1026
00:59:00.408 --> 00:59:00.588
that?

1027
00:59:00.868 --> 00:59:04.248
Yeah. So, the answer that I'll give is not law,

1028
00:59:05.008 --> 00:59:08.808
and it's not necessarily widely a rule, and every clinic has different

1029
00:59:09.028 --> 00:59:11.008
understandings of how to assess response.

1030
00:59:12.548 --> 00:59:16.048
But our practice is based on the idea that

1031
00:59:16.228 --> 00:59:20.008
perhaps the PSA kinetics are rising despite the first cycle due to rapid

1032
00:59:20.068 --> 00:59:22.708
increase in tumor before they start treatment.

1033
00:59:22.748 --> 00:59:25.998
Then you get blunting of response after the first cycle, and then you may finally

1034
00:59:26.028 --> 00:59:29.808
start to see some kind of tumor response, either leveling off or decrease

1035
00:59:29.868 --> 00:59:33.808
of the PSA. In our clinic, we've mostly followed patients with

1036
00:59:33.828 --> 00:59:37.398
PSA monitoring. Our clinic does not do a lot of

1037
00:59:37.398 --> 00:59:41.348
post-treatment SPECT imaging, which some clinics do

1038
00:59:41.488 --> 00:59:43.688
post-treatment SPECT imaging on all patients.

1039
00:59:44.528 --> 00:59:48.168
The primary way that we assess

1040
00:59:48.208 --> 00:59:51.928
response for our patients would be PSA kinetics and then interim

1041
00:59:51.968 --> 00:59:55.788
PSMA PET. Different ways that clinics are doing this are every

1042
00:59:55.808 --> 00:59:59.528
fraction post-treatment SPECT imaging using a CZT or sodium

1043
00:59:59.588 --> 01:00:01.028
iodide, SPECT, whatever you have,

1044
01:00:02.008 --> 01:00:05.648
a PET after three cycles or a PET after two cycles, and some

1045
01:00:05.788 --> 01:00:09.218
clinics are doing a PET at two cycles and a PET at four cycles as

1046
01:00:09.248 --> 01:00:12.548
well. So there's a little bit of variability, and then there's a lot of active

1047
01:00:12.568 --> 01:00:15.728
discussion on what is the best way to monitor these patients on treatment.

1048
01:00:16.088 --> 01:00:17.448
There's not a harmonized answer.

1049
01:00:18.028 --> 01:00:18.268
Thank you.

1050
01:00:19.268 --> 01:00:21.848
Okay, we have about three questions online.

1051
01:00:21.888 --> 01:00:23.948
I'll do rapid fire in the last minute here.

1052
01:00:24.008 --> 01:00:24.128
So,

1053
01:00:25.158 --> 01:00:28.068
do you have any thoughts on sequencing alpha versus beta if you were going to give

1054
01:00:28.108 --> 01:00:30.768
them to the same patient over time?

1055
01:00:30.848 --> 01:00:33.338
Number two, do you get any toxicities,

1056
01:00:34.388 --> 01:00:38.348
GI related, in that astatine-211-PTT with that intestinal

1057
01:00:38.368 --> 01:00:42.188
distribution? Number three, do you have any thoughts on rhenium-188

1058
01:00:42.228 --> 01:00:43.648
relative to other beta or alphas?

1059
01:00:44.048 --> 01:00:46.540
Okay.So we'll start with the last question first.

1060
01:00:46.600 --> 01:00:49.540
I don't have thoughts on radium-228, so we'll just move on to the next one.

1061
01:00:50.540 --> 01:00:52.520
In regards to the GI toxicity,

1062
01:00:54.500 --> 01:00:56.160
this has not been done in humans yet.

1063
01:00:56.940 --> 01:01:00.819
We hope to complete the IND-enabling work by the

1064
01:01:00.960 --> 01:01:01.660
end of this year

1065
01:01:02.700 --> 01:01:04.560
or next year, really, to get this going.

1066
01:01:05.220 --> 01:01:08.500
But fractionated treatment will probably, and hopefully, mitigate a substantial

1067
01:01:08.560 --> 01:01:11.520
amount of the GI toxicity that is expected.

1068
01:01:11.960 --> 01:01:13.990
Again, single high-dose fractionated treatment

1069
01:01:15.260 --> 01:01:16.080
was lethal

1070
01:01:17.160 --> 01:01:21.070
to mice. In regards to sequencing, there isn't

1071
01:01:21.120 --> 01:01:24.500
an understanding of optimal sequencing quite yet.

1072
01:01:24.520 --> 01:01:27.760
There are some data, for example, the RALLU study that suggests that

1073
01:01:27.820 --> 01:01:29.760
sequential treatment could be safe.

1074
01:01:30.260 --> 01:01:34.100
So if patients have sufficient hematologic parameters to go on to a next treatment,

1075
01:01:34.200 --> 01:01:37.100
they can receive it. They may have a limited response.

1076
01:01:38.100 --> 01:01:41.980
And then the Alphabet trial, trying both of those types of agents at

1077
01:01:42.020 --> 01:01:45.800
the same time. In the future, it may be that you

1078
01:01:45.840 --> 01:01:49.740
give alpha therapies

1079
01:01:49.800 --> 01:01:52.460
for biochemical relapse, maybe without measurable disease.

1080
01:01:52.520 --> 01:01:56.160
This is pie in the sky stuff. And if they have bulky disease in the future, maybe

1081
01:01:56.220 --> 01:01:58.240
you give dosimetrically derived lutetium.

1082
01:01:58.300 --> 01:02:02.260
Again, quite pie in the sky stuff. We don't know the optimal sequencing yet.

1083
01:02:03.960 --> 01:02:04.600
Thank you, everybody.

1084
01:02:10.860 --> 01:02:12.340
Okay. And I have the

1085
01:02:13.540 --> 01:02:16.920
privilege to be the additional final speaker here for this session.

1086
01:02:17.460 --> 01:02:21.250
My name is Zach Morris. I'm the chair of the Department of Radiation Medicine at

1087
01:02:21.260 --> 01:02:22.190
the University of Wisconsin,

1088
01:02:23.020 --> 01:02:23.370
and

1089
01:02:24.600 --> 01:02:25.720
these are my disclosures.

1090
01:02:28.960 --> 01:02:32.800
So, to wrap up this session, I'll focus on, as a physician

1091
01:02:32.880 --> 01:02:35.380
scientist, some preclinical and translational work

1092
01:02:36.380 --> 01:02:36.880
spanning

1093
01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:41.540
lab and phase one investigations, looking at

1094
01:02:41.600 --> 01:02:44.740
opportunities where we may combine radiopharmaceuticals with

1095
01:02:45.180 --> 01:02:46.860
other cancer treatment modalities.

1096
01:02:47.540 --> 01:02:51.390
And I think there's enormous opportunity in this space, broadly speaking.

1097
01:02:51.740 --> 01:02:55.139
As a radiation oncologist, I'll lead off with the opportunity to combine with

1098
01:02:55.160 --> 01:02:58.780
external beam radiation. Much of what our lab focuses on also has

1099
01:02:58.820 --> 01:03:00.860
been combinations with immunotherapy.

1100
01:03:01.460 --> 01:03:01.760
I think,

1101
01:03:02.600 --> 01:03:05.820
in any of these type of combination approaches, the thought between

1102
01:03:06.400 --> 01:03:09.220
combinations with alpha versus beta brings in

1103
01:03:10.220 --> 01:03:14.180
rich opportunities for radiobiology, and I think investment in

1104
01:03:14.240 --> 01:03:18.220
preclinical and scientific studies is really critical here to optimize

1105
01:03:18.260 --> 01:03:18.980
these combinations.

1106
01:03:19.840 --> 01:03:21.899
There are a number of other opportunities which I'm not going to go into.

1107
01:03:21.920 --> 01:03:22.740
I just will mention

1108
01:03:23.740 --> 01:03:27.730
the opportunity to combine with molecular-targeted therapies is enormous,

1109
01:03:27.940 --> 01:03:31.920
and we just had a paper accepted on combination with,

1110
01:03:31.940 --> 01:03:34.280
for example, DNA damage modulators.

1111
01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:35.600
So definitely,

1112
01:03:36.500 --> 01:03:40.240
many opportunities beyond what I can cover in one talk today.

1113
01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:45.800
One of the agents that I'll talk about here, in particular in our

1114
01:03:45.840 --> 01:03:49.649
preclinical as well as early-phase clinical studies, is NM-600.

1115
01:03:49.680 --> 01:03:52.760
It's developed by my colleagues, Jamie Weickert, Rainier Hernandez.

1116
01:03:53.680 --> 01:03:56.740
I do have a conflict of interest here in that I'm on the advisory board and serve

1117
01:03:56.780 --> 01:03:59.780
as a chief medical officer for Arkeis Technologies, which is commercializing this

1118
01:03:59.820 --> 01:04:00.120
product.

1119
01:04:00.960 --> 01:04:04.700
It's taken up in the membranes of tumor cells in

1120
01:04:04.740 --> 01:04:08.640
cholesterol-rich domains, and in that way is not specific

1121
01:04:08.700 --> 01:04:12.400
to one certain type of cancer, but can take

1122
01:04:12.420 --> 01:04:16.140
advantage of the theranostic capabilities to be selective, potentially, across

1123
01:04:16.260 --> 01:04:17.500
many different types of cancer.

1124
01:04:18.880 --> 01:04:22.440
And with an agent like that, there's a huge opportunity, I believe,

1125
01:04:22.820 --> 01:04:25.560
for combination with external beam radiation.

1126
01:04:26.180 --> 01:04:29.970
Using a precursor to this, CLR 131, our

1127
01:04:30.580 --> 01:04:34.420
team at the University of Wisconsin, under support from a NIH Head and Neck Spore

1128
01:04:34.500 --> 01:04:38.460
grant, led a phase one study in recurrent

1129
01:04:38.800 --> 01:04:41.780
head and neck cancer patients where we

1130
01:04:43.200 --> 01:04:46.860
determined a prescribed treatment dose of external beam radiation

1131
01:04:47.360 --> 01:04:51.260
and then did a single imaging study with this theranostic agent

1132
01:04:51.620 --> 01:04:55.500
and performed personalized dosimetry to determine the dose

1133
01:04:55.560 --> 01:04:59.500
that could be given from this agent safely while respecting,

1134
01:04:59.660 --> 01:05:03.610
in this case, renal toxicity limits, 23 gray to the

1135
01:05:03.660 --> 01:05:07.480
kidney, and then simply subtracted that dose from the planned

1136
01:05:07.540 --> 01:05:11.420
external beam so that we could potentially give the intended dose of

1137
01:05:11.500 --> 01:05:14.820
radiation to the tumor while reducing off-target

1138
01:05:15.520 --> 01:05:18.420
in the setting of recurrent head and neck cancer, where off-target dose from

1139
01:05:18.480 --> 01:05:22.200
external beam can be quite toxic. And this illustrates the

1140
01:05:22.580 --> 01:05:26.560
potential of these types of approaches, where we can deliver on-target

1141
01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:29.160
additive effects of radiation dose.

1142
01:05:29.740 --> 01:05:33.440
However, we can reduce off-target effects from both modalities,

1143
01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:37.220
potentially, or escalate dose to the target tumor, because

1144
01:05:37.260 --> 01:05:41.160
our organs at risk for most radiopharmaceuticals do not

1145
01:05:41.240 --> 01:05:44.720
overlap much with the organs at risk from external beam radiation.

1146
01:05:45.340 --> 01:05:49.100
And as radiation oncologists like Neil and I see

1147
01:05:49.140 --> 01:05:52.860
patients each day, it's that last bit of radiation, that

1148
01:05:52.900 --> 01:05:56.740
last fraction, that last gray, that often dictates the

1149
01:05:56.760 --> 01:06:00.480
degree or presence of toxicities, because when we push the dose,

1150
01:06:00.520 --> 01:06:02.800
we're pushing up against toxicity limits.

1151
01:06:03.400 --> 01:06:07.300
And it also dictates the likelihood of achieving local control or even

1152
01:06:07.360 --> 01:06:11.350
cure. And so the ability to combine these types of treatments,

1153
01:06:11.380 --> 01:06:15.290
I think, is a huge opportunity that I hope the field takes a very close look at,

1154
01:06:15.920 --> 01:06:19.840
because this is where we may see some of those curative impacts of treatment that

1155
01:06:19.880 --> 01:06:23.720
Neil highlighted. And just to illustrate that, this is a patient with a

1156
01:06:23.760 --> 01:06:27.520
recurrent adenoid cystic carcinoma in that trial, very

1157
01:06:27.560 --> 01:06:30.460
difficult to treat cancer, was able to receive

1158
01:06:31.300 --> 01:06:35.200
the radiopharmaceutical in combination with external beam, had quite an effective

1159
01:06:35.280 --> 01:06:36.000
response to that.

1160
01:06:38.260 --> 01:06:41.860
The areas where I think these types of approaches may be most impactful are

1161
01:06:42.400 --> 01:06:46.320
when we think about our normal tissue toxicity profiles

1162
01:06:46.440 --> 01:06:50.420
and our tumor response profiles, we typically are talking about

1163
01:06:50.480 --> 01:06:54.380
sigmoidal curves. Dose response curves typically are sigmoidal, and the gap

1164
01:06:54.400 --> 01:06:58.260
between those two curves, the normal tissue and the tumor, is our therapeutic

1165
01:06:58.320 --> 01:06:58.640
window.

1166
01:07:00.108 --> 01:07:03.948
That gap is narrow. We have a limited therapeutic window, so the normal tissues

1167
01:07:04.108 --> 01:07:08.068
are pushing down our dose limits. And when the dose

1168
01:07:08.108 --> 01:07:11.488
that we're delivering is still on the upslope,

1169
01:07:11.648 --> 01:07:14.868
the vertical of that sigmoid curve,

1170
01:07:15.688 --> 01:07:18.588
that to me is the most immediate opportunity.

1171
01:07:18.668 --> 01:07:22.568
So those patients where a normal tissue is limiting

1172
01:07:22.588 --> 01:07:26.528
how much we can give from external beam, and where we're at

1173
01:07:26.568 --> 01:07:30.348
a relatively low dose, so we're adding more dose to the tumor, would have a

1174
01:07:30.468 --> 01:07:32.288
significant effect on tumor control.

1175
01:07:33.788 --> 01:07:37.068
One example where I think we could achieve that is in diseases like

1176
01:07:37.108 --> 01:07:40.488
medulloblastoma, where these tend to be very radiation

1177
01:07:40.608 --> 01:07:44.468
sensitive. However, because they occur in the base of the brain

1178
01:07:44.908 --> 01:07:48.528
and they distribute potentially throughout the cerebrospinal fluid, we have a very

1179
01:07:48.668 --> 01:07:52.548
large target, craniospinal radiation, and what

1180
01:07:52.588 --> 01:07:56.388
we're trying to do here is essentially clear CSF fluid of

1181
01:07:56.428 --> 01:08:00.288
tumor cells. However, to do that, the current standard of care requires

1182
01:08:00.348 --> 01:08:04.168
use of proton beam radiation, and in exchange for treating the CSF, we're

1183
01:08:04.248 --> 01:08:07.268
also unfortunately treating the whole brain and the vertebral

1184
01:08:07.308 --> 01:08:10.328
column. This is a treatment that I think could be much better

1185
01:08:10.488 --> 01:08:13.848
achieved with molecular targeted radiopharmaceuticals, potentially

1186
01:08:13.908 --> 01:08:17.579
intrathecally injected into that CSF fluid, taking

1187
01:08:17.608 --> 01:08:21.268
advantage of the molecular targeting of that to potentially reduce the dose of

1188
01:08:21.308 --> 01:08:25.208
external beam. We do know that the toxicities of whole brain radiation occur

1189
01:08:25.228 --> 01:08:29.148
at relatively low doses, which currently puts a ceiling on how much dose we can

1190
01:08:29.248 --> 01:08:29.508
give.

1191
01:08:30.529 --> 01:08:33.568
And if we could reduce that, it's very likely we would reduce toxicities.

1192
01:08:33.588 --> 01:08:37.348
In fact, that's been seen already when we reduce the dose of external beam.

1193
01:08:37.888 --> 01:08:41.728
But what's also been seen is that when we do that, we lose tumor

1194
01:08:41.748 --> 01:08:44.088
control. So these are opportunities.

1195
01:08:44.168 --> 01:08:47.998
I won't go more into this, but I think this is a huge opportunity for our

1196
01:08:48.029 --> 01:08:51.968
field at the interface of radiation therapies to improve

1197
01:08:52.048 --> 01:08:52.608
patient care.

1198
01:08:55.909 --> 01:08:59.888
I'll transition now to much of what our lab focuses on, which are

1199
01:08:59.968 --> 01:09:03.558
the immunoradiological effects of radiopharmaceuticals,

1200
01:09:04.288 --> 01:09:07.928
and how we might, through understanding of these, rationally

1201
01:09:08.027 --> 01:09:10.748
combine immunotherapies and radiopharmaceuticals.

1202
01:09:11.998 --> 01:09:15.508
There are many different effects of radiation in the tumor immune microenvironment.

1203
01:09:15.529 --> 01:09:19.348
Some of these are positive, and some of them are negative when we consider them in

1204
01:09:19.369 --> 01:09:21.678
light of the potential anti-tumor immune response.

1205
01:09:22.489 --> 01:09:24.548
They vary in their dose responsiveness.

1206
01:09:24.718 --> 01:09:28.529
Some occur at low doses, some require high doses to achieve, and they

1207
01:09:28.568 --> 01:09:29.928
occur over different time courses.

1208
01:09:29.989 --> 01:09:33.829
This is a wholesale remodeling on

1209
01:09:33.888 --> 01:09:37.508
some level of the tumor immune microenvironment following administration of

1210
01:09:37.529 --> 01:09:41.428
radiation. We see inflammatory cytokine release almost immediately.

1211
01:09:41.489 --> 01:09:45.248
We see local depletion of radiation sensitive lineages, particularly

1212
01:09:45.288 --> 01:09:49.128
lymphocytes. But because of that inflammation, we see a rebound,

1213
01:09:49.288 --> 01:09:52.748
often increase in those. That includes a rebound in both

1214
01:09:52.788 --> 01:09:55.888
